  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Panama's immigration process is straightforward but requires good documentation and typically a local lawyer. Most applications are processed within 3-8 months.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Qualified Investor Visa Application Process</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Make Investment</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Purchase $300,000+ property with clear title, OR deposit $300,000 in Panamanian bank (3-year fixed term). Obtain proof of investment (title deed or bank certificate).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Gather Documents</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Passport, police clearance (apostilled), birth certificate (apostilled), proof of investment, health certificate, passport photos. Documents must be translated to Spanish if not already.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Hire Immigration Lawyer</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Engage Panamanian immigration lawyer to prepare and submit application. They handle National Immigration Service (SNM) filings, follow-ups, and any issues. Cost: $3,000-8,000.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Submit Application</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Lawyer submits to SNM. Receive temporary permit while processing. Processing: 3-6 months. May request additional documents during review.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Receive Temporary Residence</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Upon approval, receive 2-year temporary residence permit. Get E-Cedula (digital ID). Can live, work, and travel freely. Valid for 2 years.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Convert to Permanent Residence</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">After 2 years, apply for permanent residence (residencia permanente). Same lawyer typically handles. Straightforward if investment maintained. Permanent residence is indefinite.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Friendly Nations Visa Process</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Establish Economic Tie</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Choose your economic tie: purchase any property (no minimum value), form Panama corporation (~$1,500), or secure employment with Panama company. Property is most common choice.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Open Bank Account</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Open Panamanian bank account and deposit $5,000+. Banks are cautious with new foreign accounts—may need introduction or reference. Lawyer can assist with bank introductions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Gather Documents & Apply</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Same documents as Qualified Investor (passport, police clearance, etc.). Plus proof of economic tie and bank deposit. Lawyer submits to SNM. Processing: 4-8 months.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Receive Residence & Path to PR</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Same path as Qualified Investor: 2-year temporary → permanent residence. Same citizenship timeline (5 years as PR). Lower initial investment but same end result.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Lawyer essential:</strong> While not technically required, a good immigration lawyer is practically essential. They navigate SNM bureaucracy, prepare documents correctly, and handle issues. Cost ($3,000-8,000) is worth avoiding delays and rejections. Get referrals from expat community.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

