  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Bank Account Challenges</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Panama banks are cautious with new foreign accounts due to compliance requirements. Opening an account can take weeks or months. Start early, use lawyer introductions, bring thorough documentation (tax returns, reference letters). Don't assume you can walk in and open an account.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Poor Property Due Diligence</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Panama has titled and untitled (rights of possession) property. For investment visa, you need properly titled property with clear ownership. Use a local real estate attorney (separate from immigration lawyer). Title searches are essential. Some expats have been burned by unclear titles.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Immigration Lawyer</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">DIY applications frequently face delays and rejections. The $3,000-8,000 lawyer fee is worth it for smooth processing. They know current requirements, have SNM relationships, and handle issues. Get referrals from expat groups, not random internet lawyers.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming No Taxes</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Panama has territorial taxation—foreign income isn't taxed. But Panama-sourced income IS taxed. If you earn money from Panama clients or rent out your Panama property, you owe Panama taxes. Consult a tax professional for proper structuring. Don't assume "tax haven" means no taxes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Citizenship Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Citizenship requires 5 years as permanent resident PLUS genuine ties and physical presence. Simply holding residency isn't enough—you need to demonstrate actual living in Panama. Spanish language requirement for naturalization. If citizenship is your goal, plan to spend significant time in Panama.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

