        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I become a Panamanian citizen?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 5 years as permanent resident with genuine ties to Panama (physical presence, Spanish language, community integration), you can apply for naturalization. Process takes 1-2 years. Spanish proficiency required. Not automatic—you must apply and demonstrate ties. Dual citizenship allowed with many countries.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is territorial taxation?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Panama only taxes income sourced within Panama. Foreign income (US pension, rental income from property abroad, foreign business income) is not taxed. If you earn money from Panama activities (local clients, Panama property rental), that is taxable. This makes Panama attractive for international income earners.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work in Panama with investor visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Unlike some countries, Panama investor visas allow work. You can be employed by Panama companies, run businesses, or work remotely for foreign clients. The residency permit includes work authorization. No separate work permit needed.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What are Pensionado benefits?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Anyone receiving a pension of $1,000+/month (any nationality, any age with pension) can register for Pensionado. Benefits: 25% off restaurant meals, 25% off airline tickets, 20% off medical consultations, 15% off dental, 50% off entertainment, plus utility discounts. Significant lifestyle savings.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the Friendly Nations Visa still available?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, the Friendly Nations Visa is active as of 2026. Requirements have tightened over the years (economic tie now required), but it remains one of the easiest residency paths in the Americas. The list of eligible countries (50+) includes most Western nations. Check current requirements with Panama immigration or lawyer.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to live in Panama full-time?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No minimum stay requirement for maintaining residency. Many residents spend part of the year in Panama and part elsewhere. However, for citizenship, you must demonstrate genuine ties and physical presence (typically 180+ days/year). Residency can be maintained with minimal presence; citizenship requires substantial presence.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Panama offers one of the most attractive investor residency programs in the Americas. The Qualified Investor Visa ($300,000) provides a straightforward path to permanent residence and eventual citizenship. For citizens of Friendly Nations (US, UK, Canada, EU, etc.), the $5,000 deposit option makes Panama one of the most accessible residency destinations anywhere.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The combination of US dollar economy, territorial taxation, modern infrastructure, and clear path to citizenship makes Panama compelling for investors, retirees, and remote workers. The famous Pensionado discounts add significant lifestyle value for anyone with a pension.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Health insurance isn't mandatory but is practically essential for quality private care. International plans offer the best coverage, with easy access to US healthcare just 2.5 hours away in Miami. Budget $200-500/month for good coverage.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Panama suits investors and retirees seeking Americas base with US dollar, territorial taxation, and citizenship path. Qualified Investor ($300K) is straightforward; Friendly Nations ($5K + economic tie) is one of the easiest residency programs in the world. Come for the tax benefits and lifestyle—stay for the path to citizenship.
      </p>
